<br>
The study (Nick Yee's Norrathian Scrolls) you reference I was part of. Mr. Yee did not advertise his need of subjects in game, where he would be able to get a well balanced selection of players. Instead news of the study was posted on common information sites that the majority of the casual EverQuest players don't bother reading. The numbers speak for themselves. Out of a playerbase of 400,000 some odd, only 3,100 some odd took part. News of the study only reached the people who play so investedly that they seek out EQ related issues out of game. While I find Yee's theorizations quite interesting, his statistics are hardly unbiased. <br>
<br>
Your reference to EverQuest being linked to the suicides of two players was a cheap shot at sensationalizing others depression for the sake of your story. The logic being used by the loved ones of the deceased is clouded and emotional, and I can not find it in me to blame the families for trying to cling onto any reason for such a tragic event. I can, and will, blame yellow journalists such as yourself for reinforcing these family's belief that a game has killed their dear ones, preventing them from stripping away the layers of symptoms to find the real cause of sorrow. <br>
<br>
I am a member of EverQuest Widows, the Yahoo E-Group you mention. After having spent several months reading through the posts on the group, I have come to the conclusion that scapegoating has become a popular passtime. Many posts completely ignore logic, contradict themselves, and do nothing but bash and demean the people these 'widows' claim to love. My experience with the group has further enforced in my mind that EverQuest addiction is only a cyber-symptom of real life depression. <br>
<br>
I am an EverQuest player, Mr. Simmons. I play maybe 10 hours a week or so now, although there was a time I played 12 hours a day when I had nothing else to do. I've never forsaken a healthy, active lifestyle for a pixelated existance. I have a boyfriend who loves me and sometimes watches over my shoulder, laughing at my in game antics. I've never lost a job due to EverQuest, or dropped out of a school of higher education. I've met several people offline that I met in game, and I am proud to say that they have become good friends of mine, despite them having left EverQuest for other games, or pursuits. I am an attractive, educated female with no physical or mental illnesses. I am a more accurate representative of the EverQuest population than the two poor souls who killed themselves. However, you never hear about a flight until it crashes. Don't crash any planes to boost your career. It would not be wise.<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
Too bad he probably won't read past the first 100 &quot;You sux0rz, I pwn u&quot; emails.<br>
<br>
~ The Necrobabe formerly known as Sycha<br>
